


     LLLLSSSS((((UUUU1111))))               LLLLSSSS----DDDDOOOOSSSS 6666 ---- UUUUttttiiiilllliiiittttiiiieeeessss 1111                LLLLSSSS((((UUUU1111))))



     NNNNaaaammmmeeee
          LS - Displays directory contents

     SSSSyyyynnnnttttaaaaxxxx
          llllssss [ ----1111aaaabbbbddddllllmmmmppppttttuuuuxxxxzzzz////....!!!!????hhhh ] [ _w_i_l_d_s_p_e_c ][ :_d_r_i_v_e_s_p_e_c ]...
          [>[>] _f_i_l_e | _d_e_v_i_c_e ] [ ; _n_e_x_t _c_o_m_m_a_n_d ]

     DDDDeeeessssccccrrrriiiippppttttiiiioooonnnn
          _L_s lists the files on the specified drives.  If a _w_i_l_d_s_p_e_c
          is specified, all files that match the _w_i_l_d_s_p_e_c will be
          displayed.  If a _d_r_i_v_e_s_p_e_c is specified, only files on that
          particular drive or drives will be displayed.  If the
          _d_r_i_v_e_s_p_e_c is omitted, all directories on all active drives
          are displayed.

          By default, the files are displayed in columns and are
          sorted alphabetically.  Specifying options can cause
          additional information to be displayed, alter the sorting
          order, or change the format of the display.

          _L_s accepts several options.  Options are specified by single
          characters, and they may be entered in upper or lowercase.
          Options are always preceded by a hyphen (a "-").  If you are
          specifying multiple options, you can specify the options in
          any of these formats:
                -a -b -c   or   -abc   or   -a -bc   or  -ab -c

          The options are:

          ----1111   Only one file is listed on each line.  This is useful
               for building lists of files that will be used by other
               programs.

          ----aaaa   "All Files".  Files that are marked "invisible" will be
               displayed along with the rest of the files.

          ----bbbb   Sorts the files in reverse (Backwards) order.  By
               default the file named "AAAA" (or the file with the most
               recent date) would be displayed first.

          ----dddd   The logical drive number is appended to each filename
               displayed.

          ----llll   Each file is displayed in a long format, showing the
               size, date and permissions.  This option provides
               information similar to that found in the system DIR (A)
               command.








     Page 1                                             May 15th, 1993






     LLLLSSSS((((UUUU1111))))               LLLLSSSS----DDDDOOOOSSSS 6666 ---- UUUUttttiiiilllliiiittttiiiieeeessss 1111                LLLLSSSS((((UUUU1111))))



               In the long format, a list of attributes are displayed
               for each file.  These are represented by the characters
               ddddssssiiiiffffooooccccuuuunnnn.   If the file has a particular attribute, the
               letter is displayed.  If the file doesn't have that
               attribute, a "----" is displayed instead.

               d     The file is a PDS (Partition Data Set) or a
                     DiskDisk subdirectory.
               s     The file is a system file, usually part of the
                     operating system.
               i     The file is marked invisible and is displayed
                     only if the ----aaaa option is specified.
               f     The file has a fixed size.
               o     The file is marked "open".  If the OS is running
                     in networked mode, files are marked this way so
                     that only one application can have write access
                     at a time.
               c     The file is copy-protected.
               u     The file has a user-password (only on pre-LS-DOS
                     6.3 and pre-LDOS 5.3 versions).
               n     The file has been modified since the last time
                     _b_a_c_k_u_p(L) made a copy of this file.

               The protection attribute for each file is also listed.
               Normally it is FFFFuuuullllllll, but if the file has an Owner
               Password, it can be any of the following:

               Full      The file has no restrictions on access.
               Remove    The file attributes cannot be changed but all
                         other access is allowed.
               Rename    The file cannot removed, but all other access
                         is allowed.
               Write     The file can be read or written but not
                         removed or renamed.
               Update    The file can be read and updated, but cannot
                         be removed, renamed or change size.
               Read      The file can be read or executed, but no
                         other access is allowed.
               Execute   The file can be executed, but cannot be read
                         or modified.
               None      Without the Owner Password, the file cannot
                         be accessed.

               If a file is accessed with the Owner Password, full
               access is always allowed.  On older TRSDOS and LDOS
               versions, if the file has a User Password and an Owner
               Password, no access is allowed at all unless one of the
               two passwords are known.


          ----mmmm   Files are displayed in the stream format, separated by
               commas.  (Ignored if ----llll or ----xxxx is specified.)



